<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="7" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1887,2030]" lastBlockId="6.[151,1437,151,255]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="7" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,320,1926,1952]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Remarks.</emphasis>
First record for 
<collectingCountry box="[518,627,1926,1952]" name="Tanzania" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
. However, the specimen is not typical of the species, differing from South African specimens in scutum and abdomen colour pattern; scutum with a pair of closely approximated black stripes, one along acrostichal line and the other along dorsocentral line; terga I 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1207,1222,2003,2029]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">–</emphasis>
V black laterally, broadly black on terga III 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[455,470,151,177]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">–</emphasis>
IV. The well developed pecten and yellow postpronotal lobe, clearly indicate that this specimen is not simply an aberrant 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezzi" authorityName="Bezzi" box="[636,851,190,216]" class="Insecta" family="Lauxaniidae" genus="Dacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="katonae">
<emphasis box="[636,769,191,216]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">D. katonae</emphasis>
Bezzi
</taxonomicName>
; which has a vestigial pecten, black scutum and abdomen, and fuscous to black postpronotal lobe.
</paragraph>
